<!-- WHAT IS STOICISM -->
<section id="o-que-e">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <div class="section-left">
        <span class="label">Stoicism</span>
        <h2>A philosophy that <span class="accent">demands</span> something from you.</h2>
        <p>
          Stoicism was born in Athens around 300 BC, on the painted porch of the Agora —
          the <em>Stoa Poikile</em>, which gave the school its name. But it was in Rome that it found
          its most powerful expression: in Seneca's letters written on the eve of his execution,
          in Marcus Aurelius' personal diary never intended for any reader,
          in the lessons of Epictetus taught by a former slave who became Rome's most influential philosopher.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is not positive motivation. Not mindfulness in new clothes. It is a discipline
          that asks you to look directly at what you cannot control, at death,
          at failure — and find clarity precisely there, not in spite of it.
        </p>
        <p>
          Prática Estoica exists to take this wisdom off the philosophy shelf
          and place it where it always belonged: in use, in daily life, in the decisions
          you make when no one is watching.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="section-right">
        <blockquote class="pull-quote">
          "Waste no more time arguing about what a good man should be. Be one."
          <cite>— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations · II, 5</cite>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- THE THREE PRINCIPLES -->
<section id="principios">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-top">
      <span class="label">Core concepts</span>
      <h2>Three ideas that change how you live.</h2>
      <p>Stoicism has many layers. But if you truly understand these three concepts — not as t-shirt quotes, but as real practice — the way you inhabit the world will never be the same.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="principios-grid">
      <div class="principio-card">
        <div class="principio-num">I.</div>
        <h3>Dichotomy of Control</h3>
        <p>Some things depend on us: our opinions, impulses, desires, aversions. Everything else does not. Confusing these two categories is the source of almost all human suffering.</p>
        <div class="principio-quote">
          <p>"Some things are in our control and others not."</p>
          <cite>— Epictetus, Enchiridion · 1</cite>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="principio-card">
        <div class="principio-num">II.</div>
        <h3>Amor Fati</h3>
        <p>Love of fate. Not passively accepting what happens — actively loving what is, including what hurts. The obstacle to action becomes the path forward, if you know how to look at it.</p>
        <div class="principio-quote">
          <p>"The impediment to action advances action. What stands in the way becomes the way."</p>
          <cite>— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations · V, 20</cite>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="principio-card">
        <div class="principio-num">III.</div>
        <h3>Memento Mori</h3>
        <p>Remember that you will die. Not as pessimism — as a compass. When you remember that time is finite and nothing is guaranteed, what is small becomes smaller and what is essential becomes clear.</p>
        <div class="principio-quote">
          <p>"You could leave life right now. Let that determine what you do and say and think."</p>
          <cite>— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations · VII, 69</cite>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- THE THREE PHILOSOPHERS -->
<section id="filosofos">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-top">
      <span class="label">The masters</span>
      <h2>Three men. Three opposite lives. <span class="accent">One philosophy.</span></h2>
      <p>An emperor who didn't want power. A slave who was never free. A statesman who lived in the shadow of a tyrant. All arrived at the same place.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="filosofos-grid">
      <div class="filosofo-card">
        <div class="filosofo-era">121 — 180 AD</div>
        <h3>Marcus Aurelius</h3>
        <p class="filosofo-role">Emperor of Rome</p>
        <div class="filosofo-bar"></div>
        <p>The most powerful man in the world at the time. His personal diary, never intended for publication, is today considered the most honest document of someone trying to apply philosophy under the most extreme conditions.</p>
        <span class="filosofo-obra">Meditations</span>
      </div>
      <div class="filosofo-card">
        <div class="filosofo-era">4 BC — 65 AD</div>
        <h3>Seneca</h3>
        <p class="filosofo-role">Statesman, playwright, philosopher</p>
        <div class="filosofo-bar"></div>
        <p>One of the richest and most influential people in Rome, tutor to Emperor Nero, and eventually condemned to death by him. He wrote more about Stoicism than anyone else — letters, essays, tragedies.</p>
        <span class="filosofo-obra">Letters to Lucilius</span>
      </div>
      <div class="filosofo-card">
        <div class="filosofo-era">50 — 135 AD</div>
        <h3>Epictetus</h3>
        <p class="filosofo-role">Philosopher, former slave</p>
        <div class="filosofo-bar"></div>
        <p>Born a slave, we don't know his real name. He became one of the most influential philosophers of imperial Rome. He never wrote anything — everything we know came from a student who transcribed his lectures.</p>
        <span class="filosofo-obra">Enchiridion</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- POSITIONING -->
<section id="positioning">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="pos-inner">
      <span class="label">Who this is for</span>
      <h2>For those who want to <span class="accent">live well</span> — not perform better.</h2>
      <p class="pos-sub">The Stoicism that reached the 21st century was translated as a performance tool. Resilience, productivity, emotional management. But that is not what the original texts teach. Marcus Aurelius didn't write to optimize his day. He wrote to remind himself of what really matters.</p>
      <p class="pos-sub">Here we work with the complete system: demanding, honest, virtue-oriented — not success-oriented. The version that unsettles before it relieves.</p>
